reviews.text:
Tested at 3 weeks.&#xD;
&#xD;
A really nice dark, sweet, and rich cigar recipe.  I probably can't say "artisanal swisher sweets" without looking like a jerk, so I'll call it a refined take on a lizard brain tobacco staple.  Looking at the description, I do think it's basically what you were going for.  I'm not the tobacco vocabulary guy, but I am getting a distinct wrapper type note, so that's cool.  The cocoa is probably a bolder component for me here than the fruitiness.  Opens with a heavier cocoa note with some pleasant roast coffee overtones.  Nothing too grassy in the base, so that cocoa is working pretty well. I do pick up some of that dark fruitiness on the finish, but it's playing nicely with cocoa up front.  Sweet but not gross sweet.  The milk and honey is adding some darker caramel notes but isn't swamping the texture. Comes across as fairly dry without being too harsh.   The woodier notes from the AM4A are going across as almost a light spice note, which is working well everything here.  I like the balance overall, and this is a great take on dessert tobacco that isn't just an RY4 in disguise.
